      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">Proximity Factor</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Distance</strong> in local ranking is one of Google's three core local search factors &mdash; alongside <strong>relevance and prominence</strong> &mdash; measuring the physical proximity between the searcher and a business at the moment of query. You cannot relocate your business, but you can influence how Google interprets your service area through Google Business Profile settings and location-specific landing pages.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Ranking factor group</div>
            <div class="tms-value">1 of 3 (with Relevance, Prominence)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Weighting change</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Increased Dec 2021 (Vicinity Update)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Distance is the local ranking factor you can least control &mdash; and after the 2021 Vicinity Update, it's the one that matters most for "near me" queries. Understanding how Google measures it is the difference between competing on prominence and getting shut out of the local pack entirely.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is distance in local ranking?</h2>
        <p>Distance is Google's measure of how physically close a business is to the person doing the search. In local pack results, Google Maps, and "near me" queries, distance is one of three ranking factors it publishes explicitly:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Relevance</strong> &mdash; how well the business matches the query</li>
          <li><strong>Distance</strong> &mdash; how far the business is from the searcher</li>
          <li><strong>Prominence</strong> &mdash; how well-known and well-reviewed the business is</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Distance is calculated using the searcher's location (via device GPS, IP, Wi-Fi, or an explicit "in [city]" query modifier) against the verified business address in Google Business Profile.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">The Vicinity Update &mdash; December 2021</div>
          <p>Google's <strong>Vicinity Update</strong> significantly increased distance weighting. Businesses that used to rank across a whole city on prominence alone were suddenly limited to their immediate neighbourhood. Every serious local SEO strategy since 2022 assumes distance is the heaviest signal for "near me" queries.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why distance matters</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Dominates "near me" queries.</strong> When a user types "plumber near me," proximity is now the heaviest single signal.</li>
          <li><strong>Vicinity Update aftermath.</strong> The December 2021 update permanently raised distance's weighting in local pack ranking.</li>
          <li><strong>Centroid bias still exists.</strong> Businesses near city or neighbourhood centres still get a small algorithmic boost.</li>
          <li><strong>Prominence can offset it &mdash; partially.</strong> Very strong reviews, citations, and authority let a business punch above its distance rank, but only within limits.</li>
          <li><strong>Service area businesses depend on it.</strong> For plumbers, movers, and cleaners without walk-in locations, service area configuration in GBP is the primary distance lever.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Google measures distance</h2>
        <p>Every "near me" or unqualified local query kicks off the same lookup.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Distance calculation at query time</span><br>
          1. <span class="uf-label">Detect searcher location</span> via device GPS, Wi-Fi, IP, or query modifier<br>
          2. <span class="uf-label">Filter candidate businesses</span> by relevance to the query<br>
          3. <span class="uf-label">Compute physical distance</span> to each candidate's verified address<br>
          4. <span class="uf-label">Weight distance</span> alongside relevance and prominence signals<br>
          5. <span class="uf-label">Rank the local pack</span> with distance as the heaviest post-Vicinity factor<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Service area businesses declare coverage zones</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># in Google Business Profile &rarr; Info &rarr; Service Area</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="types">Distance signals Google uses</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Signal</th><th>Where it comes from</th><th>You can influence</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Verified business address</strong></td><td>Google Business Profile</td><td>No &mdash; must be a real address</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Declared service area</strong></td><td>GBP service area settings</td><td>Yes &mdash; keep tight and accurate</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Location pages on your site</strong></td><td>Your website</td><td>Yes &mdash; one page per city/neighbourhood</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Localised content mentions</strong></td><td>On-page copy, NAP citations</td><td>Yes &mdash; consistent neighbourhood/zip mentions</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Searcher location</strong></td><td>Device GPS, IP, Wi-Fi, query</td><td>No &mdash; entirely user-side</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Centroid position</strong></td><td>Google's geographic centre of city</td><td>No &mdash; but drives layout of results</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real distance examples</h2>
        <p>Two anonymised results from local SEO audits:</p>

        <h3>1. Pizza restaurant &middot; distance vs prominence trade-off</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Same query, two candidates</span><br>
          Candidate A: <span class="uf-new">0.3 miles away</span>, 42 reviews<br>
          Candidate B: <span class="uf-old">1.2 miles away</span>, 400 reviews<br>
          Post-Vicinity result: <span class="uf-new">Candidate A ranks higher</span> for most zoomed-in "near me" queries
        </div>

        <h3>2. Law firm &middot; neighbourhood landing pages</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Dallas-area firm expanding local visibility</span><br>
          Pages built: <span class="uf-new">7 neighbourhood landing pages</span><br>
          Local pack presence: 1 neighbourhood <span class="uf-arrow">&rarr;</span> <span class="uf-new">5 neighbourhoods</span><br>
          Time to result: 12 weeks
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Distance vs prominence &mdash; which wins?</h2>
        <p>Both matter. Since 2022, distance wins more often than it used to.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Distance (Vicinity-weighted)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Heaviest single signal for "near me" queries</li>
              <li>Cannot be optimised directly &mdash; only interpreted</li>
              <li>Service area + location pages are the main levers</li>
              <li>Rewards genuinely local businesses over regional players</li>
              <li>Amplified by device-level location precision</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Prominence</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Reviews, citations, and authority signals</li>
              <li>Fully within your control</li>
              <li>Can overcome moderate distance disadvantage</li>
              <li>Slower to build &mdash; measured in months, not weeks</li>
              <li>Rarely enough to beat a closer competitor with equal prominence</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for competing on distance</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Set service areas tightly.</strong> Overclaiming a huge service area in GBP dilutes local relevance rather than expanding it.</li>
          <li><strong>Build one landing page per neighbourhood.</strong> Not a template &mdash; a real page with local content, testimonials, and nearby landmarks.</li>
          <li><strong>Use consistent NAP citations.</strong> Name, address, and phone must match exactly across GBP, your site, and directories.</li>
          <li><strong>Mention nearby landmarks and zips.</strong> Localised on-page content helps Google associate your business with a specific area.</li>
          <li><strong>Stack prominence signals in the same neighbourhood.</strong> Reviews from customers in the specific area you want to rank in are more valuable than reviews from anywhere else.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor with a geo-grid rank tracker.</strong> See how your ranking changes across the map, not just at one pin.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake &mdash; overclaiming service area</div>
          <p>Post-Vicinity, listing a 50-mile service area doesn't unlock 50 miles of rankings. It tells Google your business is a diffuse regional player and can hurt rankings in your actual home neighbourhood. Set the service area to match where you genuinely serve, not where you'd like to.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common distance mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Using a virtual office</strong> &mdash; risks GBP suspension and rarely delivers ranking benefit.</li>
          <li><strong>Fake address moves</strong> &mdash; Google's verification catches address mismatches quickly.</li>
          <li><strong>Cloned neighbourhood pages</strong> &mdash; Google detects boilerplate location pages and discounts them.</li>
          <li><strong>Assuming prominence alone will win</strong> &mdash; post-Vicinity, a closer competitor beats a stronger-but-further one.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring geo-grid tracking</strong> &mdash; single-point rank checks hide the real distance-to-ranking curve.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc helps</h2>
        <p>theStacc runs the local SEO stack that makes distance work in your favour &mdash; tight GBP service area configuration, per-neighbourhood landing pages, consistent citations, and a geo-grid tracker showing exactly where you rank. You focus on the business; we make sure Google's map treats every relevant search location as your territory.</p>

